    <h1><a name="Foreword">Foreword:</a> Breaking with the flock</h1>
    <p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Many in the Imperium refer to the Adeptus Astartes, as &quot;His Angels&quot; or other such epithets that imply that they hold a divine significance. However, this is the thinking of the flock, not the shepard. We of the Ministorum, and of His Inquisition must look at the Astartes with skepticism. While it is unquestionable historical fact that the Adeptus Astartes were developed by the God Emperor of Man to be his greatest warriors, they are just as susceptible to corruption as any others. As defenders of the faith, it is essential for the Adeptus Sororitas to understand the fallible nature of the Astartes, as they have proven time and again to be effective interdictive measures against His warriors who have fallen to the ruinous powers. To this end, we must break with the flock. All sisters from the mightiest canoness to the simplest novice must know the possibility that the children of the Emperor&apos;s sons may not always be angels, and they pose a unique political and military threat.</p>
    <p><a href="#Contents">Contents</a></p>
    <h1>Lack of Faith</h1>
    <p>The vast majority of the Adeptus Astartes do not believe in the true divinity of Our God-Emperor. There are only a few notable exemptions to this, such as the Black Templars. The lack of spiritual faith of the Adeptus Astartes leaves them uniquely vulnerable to corruption from the archenemy. There are records of Chapters, even entire Legions of Astartes who have been corrupted by nine devils. The protectors of the faith must be wary, for Astartes may carry unknown allegiances, spread poisonous ideas to the faithful, and even undermine the authority of the church and inquisition. Astartes, with their eccentric beliefs and general popularity among the common folk could potentially cause civil unrest and a deterioration of the Imperium&apos;s religious institutions. It is important for all of the Ordo Hereticus, as protectors from threats within, to hold them at arms length and make sure the simple-minded citizens to not mingle with them.</p>
    <p><a href="#Contents">Contents</a></p>
    <h1><a name="Application">Traitors</a> </h1>
    <p>The corrupted Astartes are some of the fiercest foes of humanity. However, it is unclear what would compel the finest warriors of the Imperium to turn against their God-Emperor. Some of the Ordo Hereticus have proposed that there may be particular mutations that have caused these traitors to deviate from the will of the God-Emperor. This would explain why traitors are generally from the same units. However, this does not explain why Astartes as a whole seem to be disproportionately likely to be corrupted by the ruinous powers as seen during the Horus Heresy. Unfortunately, so little is known about the time of the Horus Heresy that we cannot know the exact events that led to the bedeviling of the traitor legions. Until such a time that the corruption of Astartes is understood, it is best for all the faithful servants of the God-Emperor to understand that angels can fall.</p>
